threads.name: Anonymous
threads.com:
Do you ever wonder what life must have been like in the Ottoman Empire for Christians? Serbians had at one point had one of the biggest empires in the Balkans. Greeks were the ones who had previously ruled over much of the Eastern Roman Empire, spanning everything from the eastern tip of Italy to Mesopotamia. The Armenians, the first nation to have ever converted to Christianity, had at one point controlled many of the highlands east of the Anatolian peninsula and even parts of the eastern Mediterranean coast of what is nowadays Turkey and Syria.

And all of these people, who believed in the Messiah who had given their life for them, the man who died on the cross and came back to life of the third day, were subjects of the people who rejected divine nature of their Messiah and denied his resurrection.

Could it not have felt to them that God had abandoned them in favor of people who must have seemed to them like heathens?
The same people whom their ancestors had fought against and even called Satan-worshippers were the ones whom they had to pay taxes to and be forced to sell their children off to pay their debts.
In case a war ever took place, they were the ones who were most likely to be levied. I wouldn't be surprised if there were many wars fought between the Ottoman Empire and Christian kingdoms like Russia or Hungary in which the majority of soldiers on both sides were Christian, except that some fought with God on their side, whereas the others were fighting against the side of God.
How could this by itself not be soul-crushing for the Serbian and Caucasian Christian soldiers of the Ottoman Empire? What drove them not to give up even in spite of being aware that they were fighting against their own interests?

These questions have answers that have been forever swept away by the passage of time, if they do have an answer at all.

1 / ?
I'll tell you a story from several dozen years ago.
>be me anon, lvl 17. I came from a very poor family,
>and lived in a flat on the 4th floor with my mum.
>My whole life we devoured potatoes.
>For breakfast potatoes, for lunch, potatoes, and for dinner, fucking potatoes.
>When I was younger, my mom made a fucking fool out of me and sometimes she made fries for breakfast, for lunch mashed, and in the evening crisps and I was happy.
>Once at school I told my friends what I eat, and they made fun of me, so from that point on I realized that even my own mother is making a fucking fool out of me.
But fine, since the story isn't about this. It was a day like everyday.
>It was morning, and we we're out of the only thing we ate, so I needed to go to the basement.
>I dressed up, cause it was way below 0C.
>I came down and you will never believe what I saw.

last_replies.name: p. 2
last_replies.com:
>A gigantic, two meter shit stalactite.
>Holy fuck, if I think about it now, I laugh, but right then, I didn't.
>Kurwa I expected everything from this shitty town, but a 2 meter column of shit in the basement?
>I remember at first I stood like a column, but then I ran to my mum.
>It smelled in the whole block.
>The basement doors were the shit pandora's box, which my little hands opened.
>I remember that going through the staircase I heard my neighbor Ivan yelling to his wife that she shat herself,
>and on the first floor he wanted to make a draft so he opened the door, but as soon as he opened them, it smelled even worse,
>and he closed the door with tears in his eyes.
>So I told my mum how it is. We made a meeting with the entire community of the block in our apartment, cause it was the highest floor, and the stank was the weakest.
>we apartment complex.
>It was a short talk. They said that its a shitty situation, and they will send someone.
>We waited a couple of hours, but no one came,
>and the next phone calls were useless....

last_replies.name: p. 3
last_replies.com:
>We made up a plan.
>Neighbors took some black and yellow tape and circled the stalactite, mum made some potatoes,
>and me, the youngest from our community, started ringing TV stations.
>Thanks to the internet, the story spread out quickly. In just one hour,
>there were a couple of hundred people coming to out block to take selfies with the pile of shit.
>At the end of the day, our block turned out to be a tourist attraction.
>Together with the neighbors we decided - cool. everyone's coming here and taking pics,
>and we're famous but the big shit, as it was before, it still was just there.
>Awesome solution kurwa.
>The only plus about it, was that our noses broke and we couldn't smell anything.
>Later I had a great idea. The whole night I didn't sleep, but I made tickets.
>The entrance at first costed 1000 rubels ($13), and i quickly found out, that it didn't scare away the people who wanted to see the big pile of shit, so on a daily basis, we rasied the price.
> With the neighbors we decided, that as the idea giver I'll be the cashier.
>And at the end when it starts getting warmer during spring and summer, the shit will melt, and with the money we will pay some people to clean it up, and divide the rest between us equally.
>The business was good for a couple months, cause winter lasts to about April, and it wasn't any different that year.
>I became the local baron.
>Everyone knew that I'm the one with the money from the shitty interest, so they treated me with respect, despite being the shortest one, having bad eyesight and a curve face.
>In the begining of April, when the cold weather started to be warmer and warmer, we set the day of the shitty meeting for a Sunday.
>I remember that on Saturday I RAN THE FUCK AWAY with two suitcases full of rubels and i stopped in Poland.

last_replies.name: p. 4
last_replies.com:
>I don't know the rest of the shit stalactite story, but I changed my name, surname and bought myself some land.
>I was missing the respect that I had during the career of a banker in Russia, especially when I was drinking, and I like drinking.
>I missed the times when the stalactite made me someone.
>During one of the bigger drinking parties, I was by myself cause I didn't know anyone else, I made a facebook profile, and I'm pretending to be a businessman there, and everyone knows that I have the money, but no one knows where I got it from.
>I won't tell them, since they're not asking tho.
>i reached my goal. People respect me.
>My name is Zbigniew Stonoga and this is my story.
